Tashkent, Uzbekistan (CNN)In a state-of-the art communal workspace in the Uzbekistan capital of Tashkent, Durdona Bakhronova sits surrounded by women and young students. A successful developer, who with for US tech firm Super Dispatch, she has become a mentor for scores of people -- especially women -- who are looking to see how technology can enhance their lives. Still only 25, she has made it her mission to encourage more women and young people to join her in the IT world. Born in the historical city of Bukhara, which is about a one hour's flight from the capital, Bakhronova moved to Tashkent to pursue her education. Initially drawn to biology, she says that when she realized the power of coding and programming there was no turning back. Read: Surprising street food and underground art in Uzbekistan's capital Bakhronova says initially she was one of very few women working in this field, which was disappointing because of the problem-solving skills that can come with a female perspective. "If women want to fix the issues that they have in their lives they'd better take care of it themselves and don't leave it to men ... because so many men try to build a product for everybody, but half of the population is women," she says. Watch the video to find out more 